      Most AI implementations fail because teams don't adopt them, not because the technology doesn't work. We train your people to use AI confidently in their daily work, so the tools you invest in actually deliver results.
    </p>
    <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 1rem; justify-content: center;">
      <button onclick="openModal(this)" data-source="training_hero" class="btn-primary" style="font-size: 1rem;">Request Training Quote →</button>
      <a href="#programs" class="btn-outline" style="font-size: 1rem;">See Programs ↓</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<!-- ── IMAGE / STAT BANNER ── -->
<div style="width: 100%; height: 380px; overflow: hidden; position: relative;">
  <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1522202176988-66273c2fd55f?w=1400&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="AI training workshop for business teams" loading="eager" fetchpriority="high" width="1400" height="380" style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center 40%;" />
  <div style="width: 100%; height: 100%; background: rgba(0,30,55,0.78); display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;">
    <div style="position: absolute; inset: 0; background-image: radial-gradient(circle, rgba(0,227,253,0.07) 1px, transparent 1px); background-size: 24px 24px;"></div>
    <StatStrip stats={[
      { value: "#1", caption: "Reason AI fails: poor team adoption, not bad technology" },
      { value: "Faster", caption: "Trained teams use AI tools daily, not occasionally" },
      { value: "Included", caption: "Follow-up support included after every workshop" },
    ]} />
  </div>
  <div style="position: absolute; inset: 0; background: linear-gradient(to top, #f9f9ff 0%, transparent 100%); pointer-events: none;"></div>
</div>

<!-- WHY TRAINING MATTERS -->
<section class="section" aria-labelledby="explain-heading">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="explain-split">
      <div>
        <h2 id="explain-heading" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Why Team Training Is the Missing Piece in Most AI Deployments</h2>
        <p style="color:#42474e; font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.85;">
          The single most common reason AI investments underdeliver is not the technology. The technology works. The problem is adoption. Teams that weren't trained to use AI tools effectively use them occasionally, poorly, or not at all. The licenses sit unused, the efficiency gains never materialize, and the business concludes that AI doesn't work for them, when in reality the tool was fine but the team never learned to use it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-img-wrap">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531482615713-2afd69097998?w=800&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Colleagues at a UAE company practicing AI prompts together during a hands-on workshop" loading="lazy" width="800" height="600" />
      </div>
    </div>
    <div style="max-width:800px; margin:2rem auto 0;">
      <p style="color:#42474e; font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.85; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
        Effective AI training is not a one-hour overview of what AI is. It is role-specific, hands-on instruction that teaches each person in your organization how AI helps them do their specific job better. A salesperson needs to learn how to use AI to research prospects and draft follow-ups. An operations manager needs to understand how to use AI to analyze data and generate reports. An HR professional needs to know how to use AI to draft job descriptions and screen applications. Generic training that covers "what AI is" produces teams that have learned something but changed nothing.
      </p>
      <p style="color:#42474e; font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.85;">
        The ROI of proper AI training is clear: employees who know how to use AI effectively save hours per week. Across a team of 20, that is dozens of hours recovered every week. Over a year, that is a significant productivity gain, without adding headcount or replacing any existing tools.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ── THE PROBLEM ── -->
